{"title_page": "2020 IndyCar Series", "text_new": "{{American Championship Car season\n|series = IndyCar\n|year = 2020\n|series_logo = \n|series_name = [[Nippon Telegraph and Telephone|NTT]] IndyCar Series\n|races = 15\n|start_date = June 6\n|end_date = TBA\n|season_champ = \n|manufacturer_champ = \n|rookie_of_year = \n|indy_winner = \n|oval_champ = \n|road_champ = \n|most_popular = \n|previous = [[2019 IndyCar Series|2019]]\n|next = [[IndyCar Series|2021]] \n}}\n[[File:Josef Newgarden Headshot.jpg|alt=|thumb|[[Josef Newgarden]] is the reigning [[IndyCar Series]] Drivers' Champion.]]\nThe '''2020 NTT IndyCar Series''' will be the 25th season of the [[IndyCar Series]] and the 99th official championship season of [[American Championship car racing|American open wheel racing]]. The premier event will be the [[2020 Indianapolis 500]]. [[Josef Newgarden]] will enter the season as the defending [[List of American open-wheel racing national champions|National Champion]]. [[Honda Performance Development|Honda]] will enter as the defending Manufacturers' Cup champion for the second consecutive season. It will be the first year of the Penske management after they took over in late 2019.\n\n==Series news==\n*On May 24, 2019, it was announced that [[IndyCar Series]] will schedule to introduce cockpit protection combining an Aeroscreen and the [[Halo (safety device)|Halo]] used in [[Formula 1]] from 2020 season onwards. The cockpit protection will be built by [[Red Bull Racing#Red Bull Advanced Technologies|Red Bull Advanced Technologies]] in a collaborative effort with Dallara. The combination of aeroscreen and halo is designed to improve safety standards by deflecting debris away from a driver's head and was originally developed for use in Formula One and IndyCar before its application was expanded to other open-wheel championships.<ref>{{cite web|title=INDYCAR Announces Plan For Cockpit Protection Innovation|url=http://www.indycar.com/News/2019/05/05-24-Aeroscreen-Red-Bull-announcement|work=IndyCar.com|publisher=[[IndyCar Series]]|date=May 24, 2019|accessdate=May 24, 2019}}</ref>\n*On November 3, 2019, it was announced the [[Team Penske]] owner [[Roger Penske]] had purchased the [[Indianapolis Motor Speedway]] and [[IndyCar]] as a racing league. Penske also announced he will step down as full-time race strategist.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indycar.com/News/2019/11/11-04-INDYCAR-Penske|title=INDYCAR, IMS Acquired by Penske Corporation|date=November 4, 2019|accessdate=November 4, 2019|website=IndyCar.com|publisher=Brickyard Trademarks, Inc.}}</ref> On January 6, 2020, IndyCar announced the transactions were formally complete. Penske officially becomes just the fourth owner in Indianapolis Motor Speedway's history and marks the first time since [[1946 Indianapolis 500|1945]] where ownership of the Speedway has changed hands.<ref>{{cite web|title=Penske Corp. completes acquisition of INDYCAR, IMS and IMS Productions|url=https://www.indycar.com/News/2020/01/01-06-Penske-acquisition|website=IndyCar.com|publisher=[[IndyCar Series]]|date=January 6, 2020|accessdate=January 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Contracted teams and drivers==\nThe following teams and drivers have been announced to compete in the 2020 NTT IndyCar Series season. All teams use a [[One-design#Car racing|spec]] [[Dallara]] IR18 chassis with [[Dallara DW12#Mk. III: Universal Aero Kit (2018\u2013present)|univeresal aero kit]] and [[Firestone Tire and Rubber Company|Firestone]] tires.\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 85%\"\n|-\n!Team\n!Engine\n!No.\n!class=\"unsortable\"|Driver(s)\n!Round(s)\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"|[[A. J. Foyt Enterprises]]\n|rowspan=\"5\"|[[Chevrolet]] \n|4\n|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Charlie Kimball]]<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.foytracing.com/single-post/2020/01/22/Charlie-Kimball-and-Novo-Nordisk-Join-AJ-Foyt-Racing-for-the-2020-NTT-IndyCar-Series-Season|title=Charlie Kimball and Novo Nordisk join A.J. Foyt Racing for the 2020 NTT IndyCar Series Sea