otorsport.com/indycar/news/penske-considers-mclaughlin-indycar-race/4651525/|title=Penske considering McLaughlin for IndyCar races in 2020|last=Malsher-Lopez|first=David|date=January 14, 2020}}</ref>\n|9\n|-\n|12\n|{{flagicon|AUS}} [[Will Power]]<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n|All\n|-\n|22\n|{{flagicon|FRA}} [[Simon Pagenaud]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.motorsport.com/indycar/news/pagenaud-remains-Penske-2020-indy/4396863/|title=Penske confirms Indy 500 winner Pagenaud will stay on in 2020|last=Malsher|first=David|date=May 27, 2019|work=Motorsport.com|access-date=2019-05-27|language=en-US}}</ref>\n|All\n|}\n{{legend|orange|text=R|Eligible for Rookie of the Year|border=solid 1px darkgray}}\n\n===Team changes===\n*Formula One team [[McLaren|McLaren Racing]] announced on August 1, 2019 it would join the series in 2020 in partnership with [[Arrow Schmidt Peterson Motorsports]] under the name Arrow McLaren Racing SP.<ref name=\"McLarenSPM\"/> The team will field two full-time entries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://beyondtheflag.com/2019/08/01/indycar-arrow-schmidt-peterson-motorsports-continue-two-full-time-cars-2020/|title=IndyCar: Arrow Schmidt Peterson Motorsports to continue with two full-time cars in 2020|last=Fair|first=Asher|date=August 1, 2019|website=Beyond the Flag|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-05}}</ref> As a result of [[McLaren]] partnership, the team officially agreed to end its engine partner deal with [[Honda Performance Development|Honda]] to allow [[Chevrolet]] to supply [[Schmidt Peterson Motorsports]] team as it was announced on August 9, 2019.<ref name=\"McLarenSPM\"/> On October 25, 2019, the joint venture unveiled a new logo and confirmed the team's name as Arrow McLaren SP.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.motorsport.com/indycar/news/arrow-mclaren-indycar-humility-ambition/4586280/|last=Malsher|first=David|title=Arrow McLaren SP approaches IndyCar with \"humility and ambition\"}}</ref>\n*On December 24, 2019, [[DragonSpeed]] released a schedule of six races for 2020, including the [[2020 Indianapolis 500|104th Indianapolis 500]]. While 2019 driver [[Ben Hanley]] had previously been tipped to return,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://racer.com/2019/08/30/dragonspeed-targeting-10-indycar-races-in-2020/|title=DragonSpeed targeting 10 IndyCar races in 2020|last=Pruett|first=Marshall|date=August 30, 2019|website=RACER|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> the December announcement did not confirm any drivers.<ref name=\"DragonSpeed 6\"/> On January 13, 2020, it was announced that Hanley would drive for DragonSpeed at the first round in St. Petersburg.<ref name=\"Hanley STP\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.indycar.com/News/2020/01/01-13-DragonSpeed-racing-StPete|title=Hanley, DragonSpeed set for St. Pete race|website=IndyCar.com|access-date=2020-01-13}}</ref>\n*On September 21, 2019 it was announced that [[Andretti Autosport]] would field a fifth entry for [[Colton Herta]] under the name [[Andretti Autosport|Andretti Harding Steinbrenner Autosport]], partnering with Mike Harding and George Michael Steinbrenner IV of the previously independent team [[Harding Steinbrenner Racing]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://racer.com/2019/09/21/andretti-autosport-confirms-herta-hsr-deal/|title=Andretti Autosport confirms Herta/HSR deal|publisher=Racer.com|date=September 21, 2019|accessdate=September 23, 2019}}</ref>\n*On November 8, 2019, [[Michael Shank|Meyer Shank Racing]], after competing part-time in 2017, 2018, and 2019, announced that they would expand to a full-time program in 2020 with [[Jack Harvey (racing driver)|Jack Harvey]]. The team retained its [[Honda]] power and entered a technical partnership with [[Andretti Autosport|Andretti Technologies]] after 2 years partnering with [[Arrow McLaren SP|Schmidt Peterson Motorsports]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.michaelshankracing.com/index.php/2019/11/08/autonation-siriusxm-and-meyer-shank-racing-ready-for-full-2020-ntt-indycar-season/|title=AutoNation, SiriusXM and Meyer Shank Racing Ready for Full 2020 NTT IndyCar Season|access-date=2019-11-08}}</ref>\n*On December 19, 2019, [[Dale Coyne Racing]] announced a partnership with [[2004 24 Hours of Le Mans]] winners [[Team Goh]] to run [[\u00c1lex Palou]] for the full season.<ref name=\"Palou DCR\"/>\n*On January 7, 2020, [[Dreyer & Reinbold Racing]] revealed to [[Racer (magazine)|RACER]] that they would be expanding to a 4-race program in 2020. Team owner Dennis Reinbold revealed that [[Sage Karam]] would be back with the team in 2020, but did not specify how many rounds, or which rounds, Karam would be entering.<ref name=\":2\"/> On January 10, 2020, in an interview with [[The Indianapolis Star|IndyStar]], Reinbold clarified that Karam would be driving their car in the rounds at St. Petersburg, Indianapolis, and Toronto.<ref name=\"DRR increase\"/>\n*On February 21, 2020, Citrone/Buhl Autosport, a partnership between Nick and [[Robert Citrone]] and Tom and [[Robbie Buhl]], announced their intentions to partner with an existing team to enter the IndyCar Series at the GMR Grand Prix and attempt to qualify for the [[2020 Indianapolis 500]]. On February 27, 2020, [[Rahal Letterman Lanigan Racing]] announced a partnership with Citrone/Buhl Autosport and [[Spencer Pigot]] will drive their entry in the GMR Grand Prix and the Indianapolis 500.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rahal.com/2020/02/27/spencer-pigot-to-compete-in-the-gmr-grand-prix-and-indy-500-for-rahal-letterman-lanigan-racing-with-citrone-buhl-autosport/|title=Spencer Pigot to Compete in the GMR Grand Prix and Indy 500 for Rahal Letterman Lanigan Racing With Citrone/Buhl Autosport|publisher=Rahal.com|date=February 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Driver changes===\n*On October 8, 2019 [[Chip Ganassi Racing]] announced that [[Marcus Ericsson]] would join the team, leaving Arrow Schmidt Peterson Motorsports to drive the revived No. 8 car in 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://racer.com/2019/10/08/ericsson-confirmed-for-third-ganassi-indycar-in-2020/|title=Ericsson confirmed for third Ganassi IndyCar in 2020|last=Pruett|first=Marshall|publisher=Racer.com|date=October 8, 2019|accessdate=October 8, 2019}}</ref>\n*On October 28, 2019 [[Arrow McLaren SP]] relieved [[James Hinchcliffe]] of his driving duties and signed [[2019 Indy Lights|2019]] [[Indy Lights]] champion [[Oliver Askew]] and former [[Carlin Motorsport|Carlin]] driver and [[2018 Indy Lights|2018]] Indy Lights champion [[Pato O'Ward]] to fill their two seats.<ref name=\"ArrowMcLarenDriverChange\"/>\n*On November 15, 2019, [[Ed Carpenter Racing]] announced that [[Spencer Pigot]] would not be returning to the team in 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://au.motorsport.com/indycar/news/pigot-loses-ride-with-carpenter/4597064/|title=Pigot loses his ride with Ed Carpenter Racing|last=Malsher|first=David|date=November 15, 2019|website=Motorsport.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> On November 20, ECR announced [[Rinus VeeKay]] had been signed to drive the No. 21 full-time.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://racer.com/2019/11/20/veekay-confirmed-at-ecr/ |title = VeeKay confirmed at ECR|date = 2019-11-20}}</ref>\n*On November 22, 2019, it was announced that [[S\u00e9bastien Bourdais]] would not return to [[Dale Coyne Racing]] with [[Jimmy Vasser|Vasser]]-Sullivan due to a new need for funding.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://racer.com/2019/11/22/bourdais-out-at-coyne/|title=Bourdais out at Coyne|date=November 22, 2019|website=RACER|language=en|access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref> The same day, Bourdais confirmed his exit from the IndyCar Series after signing to drive for JDC-Miller Motorsports in the [[2020 WeatherTech SportsCar Championship]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Barbosa, Bourdais to Drive JDC-Miller Cadillac DPi|url=https://sportscar365.com/imsa/iwsc/barbosa-bourdais-to-drive-jdc-miller-cadillac/|date=November 22, 2019|accessdate=November 22, 2019|first=Daniel|last=Lloyd|website=SportsCar365.com|publisher=John Dagys Media, LLC.}}</ref> On January 23, 2020, the team announced that [[Santino Ferrucci]], who drove the No. 19 car for [[Dale Coyne Racing]] in 2019, would switch to the Vasser-Sullivan-supported No. 18 entry to replace Bourdais.<ref name=\"Ferrucci DCR\"/>\n*On December 9, 2019, [[Ed Carpenter Racing]] announced that [[Conor Daly]] would contest the road and street circuit races in the team's No. 20 entry with sponsorship from the [[United States Air Force]], and would pilot a third entry for the team in the Indianapolis 500.<ref name=\":1\" /> He replaces [[Ed Jones (racing driver)|Ed Jones]], who will drive for [[W Racing Team|Audi Sport Team WRT]] in the [[2020 Deutsche Tourenwagen Masters|2020 DTM season]].<ref name=\"WRT 2020\">{{cite web|title=WRT Audi adds IndyCar racer to all-new DTM line-up|url=https://www.motorsport.com/dtm/news/audi-wrt-new-2020-lineup-jones-scherer/4611967/|last=Errington|first=Tom|publisher=[[Motorsport Network]]|work=[[Motorsport.com]]|date=December 11, 2019|accessdate=December 11, 2019}}</ref> Daly will also compete the four other oval events in [[Carlin Racing|Carlin]]'s No. 59, replacing Max Chilton who quit racing ovals in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|title=Conor Daly to run four races for Carlin in expansion to full season|url=https://motorsports.nbcsports.com/2020/03/10/conor-daly-carlin-ovals/|last=Eubanks|first=Michael|publisher=[[NBC Sports]]|date=March 10, 2020|accessdate=March 10, 2020}}</ref> \n*On January 22, 2020, [[A. J. Foyt Enterprises]] named [[Charlie Kimball]] the driver of their No. 4 entry, marking his return to full-time competition after running a partial schedule for [[Carlin Racing|Carlin]] in 2019.<ref name=\":3\" />\n* On January 29, 2020, [[Tony Kanaan]] announced that 2020 would be his final season as a primary driver in IndyCar. He will race in the five oval events in the No. 14 for [[A. J. Foyt Enterprises]].<ref name=\"kanaan\"/> On February 4, 2020 [[A. J. Foyt Enterprises]] confirmed that driving duties for the No. 14 on the road and street tracks would be split between [[S\u00e9bastien Bourdais]] and [[Dalton Kellett]]. Kellett will also drive the team's third entry in the Indianapolis 500.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indycar.com/News/2020/02/02-04-Bourdais-Kellett-to-Foyt|title=Bourdais,Kellett complete Foyt driver lineup|language=en|work=IndyCar.com|accessdate=February 4, 2020}}</ref>\n* On February 5, 2020, [[Team Penske]] confirmed that defending [[2019 Supercars Championship|Supercars]] champion [[Scott McLaughlin (racing driver)|Scott McLaughlin]] (a driver for the [[DJR Team Penske|Supercars team Penske co-owns]]) would make his IndyCar debut at the GMR Grand Prix on the Indianapolis road course. [[H\u00e9lio Castroneves]], who drove a fourth Penske car at both Indianapolis races in 2018 and 2019, will only race in the [[2020 Indianapolis 500]] for Penske.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://racer.com/2020/02/05/supercars-star-mclaughlin-set-for-indy-gp-with-penske/|title=Supercars star McLaughlin set for Indy GP with Penske|language=en|work=[[Racer (magazine)|RACER]]|accessdate=February 5, 2020|date=2020-02-05}}</ref> On March 27, 2020, it was revealed that McLaughlin would no longer be making his IndyCar debut at the GMR Grand Prix due to the rescheduling of the race. It is unclear if he will compete in any other races.<ref>{{Cite tweet|user=JennaFryer|first=Jenna|last=Fryer|number=1243710747596726273|title=Just talked to Roger Penske, one tidbit of the conversation: @smclaughlin93 will no longer make his #IndyCar debut on IMS road course due to disrupted schedule. Not enough practice time, too hectic of a weekend. But, catch him tomorrow virtually race virtual Watkins Glen!|date=March 27, 2020|accessdate=March 27, 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328021208/https://twitter.com/JennaFryer/status/1243710747596726273|archivedate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n*On February 19, 2020, [[Andretti Autosport]] announced that [[James Hinchcliffe]] would contest three events in the team's No. 29 entry with sponsorship from [[Genesys (company)|Genesys]]. He will be driving at the GMR Grand Prix, the Indianapolis 500 and the [[Texas Indy 600]].<ref name=\"Hinchcliffe AA\"/>\n*On February 25, 2020, [[Fernando Alonso]], who attempted to qualify for the Indianapolis 500 with [[McLaren|McLaren Racing]] in 2019, announced that he would be driving for Arrow McLaren SP at the [[2020 Indianapolis 500]].<ref name=\"Arrow Alonso\"/>\n*On March 10, 2020, [[Carlin Racing|Carlin]] announced that [[Felipe Nasr]], who races full-time with [[Action Express Racing]] in the [[2020 WeatherTech SportsCar Championship]], would make his IndyCar debut in St. Petersburg.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://racer.com/2020/03/10/nasr-completes-carlin-indycar-line-up-for-st-petersburg/|title=Nasr completes Carlin IndyCar line-up for St Petersburg|language=en|work=[[Racer (magazine)|RACER]]|accessdate=March 10, 2020|date=2020-03-10}}</ref>\n\n== Schedule ==\n===Initial schedule===\nThe 2020 schedule was initially announced on September 1, 2019; there was one change from the [[2019 IndyCar Series]] calendar with [[Pocono Raceway]] being replaced by [[Richmond Raceway]], the latter track returning to the series for the first time since [[2009 IndyCar Series|2009]].<ref name=\"2020 schedule\">{{cite news|url=https://www.indycar.com/News/2019/09/09-01-Cavin-Schedule-2020|title=IndyCar 2020: Richmond part of 17-race schedule|work=[[IndyCar Series]]|publisher=Brickyard Trademarks, Inc.|date=September 1, 2019|accessdate=September 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Revisions due to the coronavirus (COVID-19) pandemic===\nOn March 12, 2020, it was announced that due to the threat of the [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus]], the [[Firestone Grand Prix of St. Petersburg]] would take place [[behind closed doors (sport)|without spectators]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://racer.com/2020/03/12/indycar-st-pete-to-run-behind-closed-doors-condensed-schedule/?fbclid=IwAR2rbptkPrdiFWmEnphyp2wVtWXu9TuFawiQfhsV_9FVDN87WuwJm7mpqS8|title=IndyCar St Pete to run behind closed doors; condensed schedule|last=Miller|first=Robin|publisher=Racer.com|date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> Later that day, the city of Long Beach cancelled or postponed all large scale events through the months of March and April, resulting in the postponement of the [[Grand Prix of Long Beach]].<ref name=\"LB Postpone\">{{Cite web|url=http://longbeach.gov/press-releases/long-beach-cancels-all-large-scale-events-through-april-2020/|title=Long Beach Cancels All Large Scale Events Through April 2020|publisher=City of Long Beach|date=March 12, 2020|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> On March 18, it was announced that the race would not be rescheduled.<ref name=\"GPLB cancellation\">{{cite news|url=https://www.indycar.com/2020/ScheduleUpdates|title=2020: Latest Schedule Updates|work=[[IndyCar Series]]|publisher=Brickyard Trademarks, Inc.|accessdate=March 18, 2020|quote=The Grand Prix Association of Long Beach today announced that it will not be able to conduct the 2020 Acura Grand Prix of Long Beach at a date later in the year.}}</ref>\n\nOn March 13, 2020, IndyCar announced the cancellation/postponement of all races through the end of April, due to the coronavirus (COVID-19) pandemic.<ref>{{cite web |title=Official Statement From INDYCAR |url=https://www.indycar.com/News/2020/03/03-12-StPete-Race |website=IndyCar.com |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref> This was to mark the first time since [[1957 USAC Championship Car season|the 1957 season]] that the month of May would start the season. However, on March 26, the Indy 500, originally scheduled for May 24, was postponed to August. This marks the first time since the inaugural 500 mile race in 1911 that the race is not held in the month of May.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://covid19.ims.com/|title=Indianapolis Motor Speedway - COVID-19 Response|website=covid19.ims.com}}</ref>\n\nOn March 26, 2020, it was announced that the Firestone Grand Prix of St. Petersburg would be rescheduled to the season finale, but no date was announced.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gpstpete.com/news/257-the-firestone-grand-prix-of-st-petersburg-will-be-rescheduled-in-2020|title=Firestone Grand Prix of St. Petersburg - The Firestone Grand Prix of St. Petersburg Expected to Be Rescheduled in 2020|website=gpstpete.com}}</ref>\n\nOn April 6, 2020, it was announced the Detroit races would be cancelled because of Michigan regulations.  Iowa and Laguna Seca will become doubleheaders, and the [[Intercontinental GT Challenge]] 8 Hours of Indianapolis weekend will add an INDYCAR event Saturday: the [[Harvest Auto Racing Classic|INDYCAR Harvest GP]].<ref>{{cite web|title=DOUBLEHEADERS AT IOWA, LAGUNA SECA, THIRD EVENT AT IMS HIGHLIGHT UPDATED INDYCAR CALENDAR|url=https://www.indycar.com/News/2020/04/04-06-Schedule-Update|date=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 85%\"\n|-\n! Rd.\n! Date\n! Race name\n! Track\n! City\n! Time{{refn|group=N|All start times listed are Eastern Daylight Time. All races are covered on the radio by the [[Indianapolis Motor Speedway Radio Network|Pennzoil IndyCar Radio Network]].<ref name=\"2020 schedule\"/>}}\n|-\n! 1\n| June 6\n| [[Genesys 600]]\n| {{Color box|transparent|O|border=darkgray}} [[Texas Motor Speedway]]\n| [[Fort Worth, Texas]]\n| 8:45&nbsp;p.m.\n|-\n! 2\n| June 21\n| [[REV Group Grand Prix at Road America]]\n| {{Color box|lightblue|R|border=darkgray}} [[Road America]]\n| [[Elkhart Lake, Wisconsin]]\n| 12:50&nbsp;p.m.\n|-\n! 3\n| June 27\n| [[Indy Richmond 300]]\n| {{Color box|transparent|O|border=darkgray}} [[Richmond Raceway]]\n| [[Richmond, Virginia]]\n| 8:15&nbsp;p.m.\n|-\n! 4\n| July 4\n| [[GMR Grand Prix]]\n| {{Color box|lightblue|R|border=darkgray}} [[Indianapolis Motor Speedway#GMR Grand Prix|Indianapolis Motor Speedway Road Course]]\n| [[Speedway, Indiana]]\n| 3:50&nbsp;p.m.\n|-\n! 5\n| July 12\n| [[Honda Indy Toronto]]\n| {{Color box|lightblue|R|bord