{"title_page": "The Asian Banker", "text_new": "{{Short description|Financial services company}}\n{{COI|date=May 2017}}\n{{EngvarB|date=July 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}}\n{{Cleanup-rewrite|date=May 2009}}\n{{Infobox company\n|  name   = The Asian Banker\n|  type   = Private Company\n|  logo   = [[File:The Asian Banker.png|200px|The Asian Banker]]\n|  foundation     = 1996\n|  location       = Singapore (headquarters), [[Kuala Lumpur]], [[Beijing]], [[Dubai]]\n|  key_people     = [[Emmanuel Daniel]], President and CEO\n|  num_employees  = ~70\n| industry       = research and information for the [[financial services]] industry, publishing, consulting, training, conferences\n|  products       = [[The Asian Banker Journal]]\n[[The Asian Banker 300]]\n[[The Asian Banker Summit]]\n|  homepage       = [http://www.theasianbanker.com/ www.theasianbanker.com]\n}}\n'''The Asian Banker''' is a company that provides information for the financial services industry in the form of publications, online materials such as e-newsletters, research, and conventions, and other industry gatherings. It is regarded as one of the Asian region's leading consultancies in financial services research, benchmarking and intelligence.<ref>[http://knowledge.smu.edu.sg/article.cfm?articleid=1157 \"The Asian Banker: From Trade Journal to Industry Trendsetter,\"]. Knowledge@SMU,' 5 August 2008</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe Asian Banker was founded in Singapore in 1996 by [[Emmanuel Daniel]], a former consultant.  It was established first as a publisher of trade publication, such as [[The Asian Banker Journal]], before moving into research, consulting, benchmarking, and events organisation, all catering to the financial services industry.<ref>[http://nus.edu.sg/nec/ed/tvf/tvf-emmanueldaniel020903.html National University of Singapore, Entrepreneurship in the information business] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081018063456/http://nus.edu.sg/nec/ed/tvf/tvf-emmanueldaniel020903.html |date=18 October 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\nThe company's original product was [[The Asian Banker Journal]], a quarterly publication of 40 pages that was launched in January 1997.  Throughout 1997 and 1998, it provided on-the-ground coverage of the Asian financial crisis, anchored by Daniel's journalistic skills and award-winning articles\u2014Daniel won the prestigious Citibank Excellence in Journalism Award for the Asian region in February 1999 for his work in determining the impact of the Internet on banking.<ref>[https://www.theasianbanker.com/A556C5/homepage.nsf/0/8CC41EF3E637F54748256D09002893AA?OpenDocument About The Asian Banker] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070630003808/https://www.theasianbanker.com/A556C5/homepage.nsf/0/8CC41EF3E637F54748256D09002893AA?OpenDocument |date=30 June 2007 }}</ref>\n\nThe magazine covers a wide range of industry topics, such as opinion editorials, current events analysis, retail banking, transaction banking, risk management, bank regulation and IT for financial services. It features profiles of individuals in the financial services industry, some of which can run to several pages if the individual is particularly influential.<ref>[https://www.theasianbanker.com/A556C5/Journals.nsf/frmJournal?OpenForm&Issue=86 The Asian Banker Journal main page]{{dead link|date=July 2014}}</ref> The publication is characterised by its coverage of bank CEOs and chief regulators interviews. The publications business also maintains a video interview website called The Banking Conversation. The website contains interviews, 10 to 30 minutes in length, of prominent figures in banking, economics, IT, investing and academia.\n\nBy 2005, The Asian Banker Journal was published 10 times a year.  While Daniel has turned over management of the magazine to staff, he still writes for a blog.\n\n==Forums business==\nThe company launched a forums division in 2000 to capitalise on the interest its readership had in taking part in a forum to discuss banking issues and challenges that had come to the fore in the aftermath of the [[1997 Asian Financial Crisis]].  It held the first [[Asian Banker Summit]] in Singapore in 2000.  Subsequent summits have been held in Kuala Lumpur, Bangkok, Jakarta and Hanoi, Beijing and Singapore.\n\nThe Summit typically include fora on topics such as [[risk management]], information technology, [[transaction banking]], [[payment systems]] and regulation, and they include both opening, and closing, keynote speeches. Past keynote speakers include [[Al Gore]]<ref>[http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2005-03/18/content_2711819.htm China View, 18 March 2005, \"Al Gore Stresses sustainability of world economy\"]. News.xinhuanet.com (18 March 2005).</ref> (Summit 2005), [[William Seidman]]<ref>[http://old.thejakartapost.com/yesterdaydetail.asp?fileid=20070322.O06 Jakarta Post, 22 March 2007, \"Summit to highlight developments in Indonesian banks\"]{{dead link|date=July 2014}}</ref> (Summit 2005\u20132007), [[Thomas Bliley]] (Summit 2006), [[Paul Keating]]<ref>{{cite news | url=http://old.thejakartapost.com/yesterdaydetail.asp?fileid=20070403.F07&irec=5 | archiveurl=http://www.tmcnet.com/usubmit/2007/04/03/2461359.htm | newspaper=Jakarta Post | date=3 April 2007 | archivedate=3 April 2007 | title=China powers regional prosperity | accessdate=5 October 2014}}</ref> (Summit 2007), [[Paul Sarbanes]]<ref>[http://www.hanoitimes.com.vn/print.asp?newsid=4589 Hanoi Times, 27 March 208, \"Vietnam\u2019s economy has great potential to grow\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111004143634/http://www.hanoitimes.com.vn/print.asp?newsid=4589 |date=4 October 2011 }}</ref> (Summit 2008), [[Kaspar Villiger]] (Summit 2008), [[Jeffrey Lacker]] (Summit 2009), [[Liu Mingkang]] (Summit 2009), [[Malcolm Knight]] (Summit 2009), [[Julie Dickson]] (Summit 2009), [[Neel Kashkari]] (Summit 2010), [[Richard Kovacevich]] (Summit 2012), and [[Thomas Hoenig]] (Summit 2013).\n\nIn The Asian Banker Summit 2008 in Hanoi and The Asian Banker Summit 2009 in Beijing, The Asian Banker collaborated with [[The Bankers' Association for Finance and Trade]] (BAFT) on a conference, held in conjunction with The Asian Banker Summit, called The BAFT Asia Conference on Cash, Treasury and Trade.<ref>[http://www.asianbankerforums.com/summit2008/conference_04.php The Asian Banker Summit 2008, BAFT Asia Conference on Cash, Treasury and Trade]. Asianbankerforums.com.</ref> On 27 October 2008, BAFT announced that it had renewed the agreement for the 2009 conference in Beijing.<ref>[http://www.aba.com/Press+Room/102708BAFTAsianBanker.htm American Bankers Association, 27 October 2008, \"BAFT and The Asian Banker Renew Agreement to Collaborate on Annual Asian Summit\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081203151844/https://www.aba.com/Press+Room/102708BAFTAsianBanker.htm |date=3 December 2008 }}. Aba.com.</ref>\n\nBesides the Summit, the company holds events in other cities around Asia.<ref>[http://www.asianbankerforums.com Asian Banker Forums]. Asian Banker Forums.</ref>\n\n==Research==\nThe Asian Banker launched a research division in 2003.<ref>[https://www.theasianbanker.com/A556C5/Research.nsf/frmResDtCtr?OpenForm Asian Banker Research] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070630004025/https://www.theasianbanker.com/A556C5/Research.nsf/frmResDtCtr?OpenForm |date=30 June 2007 }}</ref> [[Asian Banker Research]] business compiles rankings, such as Asia Pacific banks by asset size and financial strength, CEO compensation, dividend payouts, the top 40 Islamic banking institutions in Asia, a databook of macro indicators of banking, payments and distribution, and industry performance. The division also writes management reports, research notes, country reports, and proprietary benchmarking on consumer banking technology and operations, and other topics.\n\n===The Asian Banker 300===\nWhile The Asian Banker's research business covers a variety of research projects, its most visible product is [[The Asian Banker 300]], a reference guide to the 300 largest banks in Asia Pacific by assets. The company expands the list to over 500 banks in its online version. The research comes out in September or October and is launched every year at [[Sibos (conference)|Sibos]], the large annual financial services convention organised by [[SWIFT]]. In the 2008 financial year, the 10 largest banks in the Asia Pacific region by assets were [[Mitsubishi UFJ Financial Group]], [[Mizuho Financial Group]], [[Industrial and Commercial Bank of China]], [[Sumitomo Mitsui Financial Group]], [[China Construction Bank]], [[Agricultural Bank of China]], [[Bank of China]], [[Norinchukin Bank]], [[Hongkong and Shanghai Banking Corporation]] and [[National Australia Bank]]. This has been unchanged since the previous years.<ref name=\"The Asian Banker 300\">[http://www.asianbankerpublication.com/A556C5/Journals.nsf/frmJournal?OpenForm&Issue=92 The Asian Banker 300]</ref>\n\nSince 2003, the guide has added a strength ranking, which measures each of the 300 banks according to a strength formula.  The formula weights assets, year-on-year growth in loans, year-on-year growth in deposits, and eight other criteria to arrive at a total strength score.<ref name=\"The Asian Banker 300\"/> Invariably, the largest banks are not necessarily the strongest banks, and in the 2009 financial year, the 10 strongest banks in the Asia Pacific region were [[HDFC Bank]], [[Punjab National Bank]], [[Public Bank]], [[Bank of Nanjing]], [[Bank Central Asia]], [[China CITIC Bank]], [[ANZ Bank New Zealand|ANZ National Bank]], [[Union Bank of India]], [[Westpac Banking Corporation]] and [[China Construction Bank]].<ref>[http://www.asianbankerpublication.com/A556C5/Journals.nsf/frmJournal?OpenForm&Issue=92 The Asian Banker list of the 300 largest banks by assets in the Asia Pacific region]</ref> The ranking is a recognised benchmark among financial institutions in Asia, and banks that have mentioned the ranking in their investor relations materials and financial reports include [[Siam Commercial Bank]],<ref>[http://www.scb.co.th/en/abt/abt_awb_50.shtml About Siam Commercial Bank, Awards and Rankings, 2007]. Scb.co.th.</ref> [[Maybank]],<ref>[http://www.maybankcms.com.ph/recent_events.html Maybank, January 2008, Maybank Ranked Among Asia Pacific\u2019s Largest and Strongest Banks] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20080627010813/http://www.maybankcms.com.ph/recent_events.html |date=27 June 2008 }}. Maybankcms.com.ph.</ref> [[Shanghai Pudong Development Bank]],<ref>[http://www.spdb.com.cn/docpage/c522/200709/0930_522_15166.aspx Shanghai Pudong Development Bank, About Us, News, SPDB Ranked Top 3 Chinese Banks] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120122024227/http://www.spdb.com.cn/docpage/c522/200709/0930_522_15166.aspx |date=22 January 2012 }}. Spdb.com.cn.</ref> [[DBS Bank|DBS]],<ref>[http://www.dbs.com.sg/dbsgroup/annual2006/Pages/awards_and_accolades.htm DBS, Awards and Accolades, Hearing it from the Marketplace]. Dbs.com.sg.</ref> [[Bumiputra-Commerce Holdings]]<ref>[http://www.cimb.com/annual_reports/BCHB/2007/pdf/exec.pdf Bumiputra-Commerce Holdings Berhad, Annual Report, 2007] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091229115910/http://www.cimb.com/annual_reports/BCHB/2007/pdf/exec.pdf |date=29 December 2009 }}</ref> and [[Hang Seng Bank]].<ref>[http://www.hangseng.com/hsb/eng/abo/cc/csr/our_bus/main_ourbus.html Hang Seng Bank, Our Business] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081204135706/http://www.hangseng.com/hsb/eng/abo/cc/csr/our_bus/main_ourbus.html |date=4 December 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.theasianbanker.com/ Official Web Site]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100316215024/http://www.asianbankerpublication.com/ The Asian Banker Editorial]\n*[http://www.asianbankerforums.com/ The Asian Banker Forums]\n*[https://www.theasianbanker.com/A556C5/Journals.nsf/frmJournal?openform&Issue=84/ The Asian Banker Journal]{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n*[https://www.theasianbanker.com/A556C5/Research.nsf/frmResDtCtr?OpenForm/ The Asian Banker Research]{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Asian Banker}}\n[[Category:Financial services companies established in 1996]]\n[[Category:Financial services companies of Singapore]]\n[[Category:Banking industry]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Financial services company}}\n{{COI|date=May 2017}}\n{{EngvarB|date=July 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}}\n{{Cleanup-rewrite|date=May 2009}}\n{{Infobox company\n|  name   = The Asian Banker\n|  type   = Private Company\n|  logo   = [[File:The Asian Banker.png|200px|The Asian Banker]]\n|  foundation     = 1996\n|  location       = Singapore (headquarters), [[Kuala Lumpur]], [[Beijing]], [[Dubai]]\n|  key_people     = [[Emmanuel Daniel]], President and CEO\n|  num_employees  = ~70\n| industry       = research and information for the [[financial services]] industry, publishing, consulting, training, conferences\n|  products       = [[The Asian Banker Journal]]\n[[The Asian Banker 300]]\n[[The Asian Banker Summit]]\n|  homepage       = [http://www.theasianbanker.com/ www.theasianbanker.com]\n}}\n'''The Asian Banker''' is a company that provides information for the financial services industry in the form of publications, online materials such as e-newsletters, research, and conventions, and other industry gatherings. It is regarded as one of the Asian region's leading consultancies in financial services research, benchmarking and intelligence.<ref>[http://knowledge.smu.edu.sg/article.cfm?articleid=1157 \"The Asian Banker: From Trade Journal to Industry Trendsetter,\"]. Knowledge@SMU,' 5 August 2008</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe Asian Banker was founded in Singapore in 1996 by [[Emmanuel Daniel]], a former consultant.  It was established first as a publisher of trade publication, such as [[The Asian Banker Journal]], before moving into research, consulting, benchmarking, and events organisation, all catering to the financial services industry.<ref>[http://nus.edu.sg/nec/ed/tvf/tvf-emmanueldaniel020903.html National University of Singaopre, Entrepreneurship in the information business] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081018063456/http://nus.edu.sg/nec/ed/tvf/tvf-emmanueldaniel020903.html |date=18 October 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\nThe company's original product was [[The Asian Banker Journal]], a quarterly publication of 40 pages that was launched in January 1997.  Throughout 1997 and 1998, it provided on-the-ground coverage of the Asian financial crisis, anchored by Daniel's journalistic skills and award-winning articles\u2014Daniel won the prestigious Citibank Excellence in Journalism Award for the Asian region in February 1999 for his work in determining the impact of the Internet on banking.<ref>[https://www.theasianbanker.com/A556C5/homepage.nsf/0/8CC41EF3E637F54748256D09002893AA?OpenDocument About The Asian Banker] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070630003808/https://www.theasianbanker.com/A556C5/homepage.nsf/0/8CC41EF3E637F54748256D09002893AA?OpenDocument |date=30 June 2007 }}</ref>\n\nThe magazine covers a wide range of industry topics, such as opinion editorials, current events analysis, retail banking, transaction banking, risk management, bank regulation and IT for financial services. It features profiles of individuals in the financial services industry, some of which can run to several pages if the individual is particularly influential.<ref>[https://www.theasianbanker.com/A556C5/Journals.nsf/frmJournal?OpenForm&Issue=86 The Asian Banker Journal main page]{{dead link|date=July 2014}}</ref> The publication is characterised by its coverage of bank CEOs and chief regulators interviews. The publications business also maintains a video interview website called The Banking Conversation. The website contains interviews, 10 to 30 minutes in length, of prominent figures in banking, economics, IT, investing and academia.\n\nBy 2005, The Asian Banker Journal was published 10 times a year.  While Daniel has turned over management of the magazine to staff, he still writes for a blog.\n\n==Forums business==\nThe company launched a forums division in 2000 to capitalise on the interest its readership had in taking part in a forum to discuss banking issues and challenges that had come to the fore in the aftermath of the [[1997 Asian Financial Crisis]].  It held the first [[Asian Banker Summit]] in Singapore in 2000.  Subsequent summits have been held in Kuala Lumpur, Bangkok, Jakarta and Hanoi, Beijing and Singapore.\n\nThe Summit typically include fora on topics such as [[risk management]], information technology, [[transaction banking]], [[payment systems]] and regulation, and they include both opening, and closing, keynote speeches. Past keynote speakers include [[Al Gore]]<ref>[http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2005-03/18/content_2711819.htm China View, 18 March 2005, \"Al Gore Stresses sustainability of world economy\"]. News.xinhuanet.com (18 March 2005).</ref> (Summit 2005), [[William Seidman]]<ref>[http://old.thejakartapost.com/yesterdaydetail.asp?fileid=20070322.O06 Jakarta Post, 22 March 2007, \"Summit to highlight developments in Indonesian banks\"]{{dead link|date=July 2014}}</ref> (Summit 2005\u20132007), [[Thomas Bliley]] (Summit 2006), [[Paul Keating]]<ref>{{cite news | url=http://old.thejakartapost.com/yesterdaydetail.asp?fileid=20070403.F07&irec=5 | archiveurl=http://www.tmcnet.com/usubmit/2007/04/03/2461359.htm | newspaper=Jakarta Post | date=3 April 2007 | archivedate=3 April 2007 | title=China powers regional prosperity | accessdate=5 October 2014}}</ref> (Summit 2007), [[Paul Sarbanes]]<ref>[http://www.hanoitimes.com.vn/print.asp?newsid=4589 Hanoi Times, 27 March 208, \"Vietnam\u2019s economy has great potential to grow\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111004143634/http://www.hanoitimes.com.vn/print.asp?newsid=4589 |date=4 October 2011 }}</ref> (Summit 2008), [[Kaspar Villiger]] (Summit 2008), [[Jeffrey Lacker]] (Summit 2009), [[Liu Mingkang]] (Summit 2009), [[Malcolm Knight]] (Summit 2009), [[Julie Dickson]] (Summit 2009), [[Neel Kashkari]] (Summit 2010), [[Richard Kovacevich]] (Summit 2012), and [[Thomas Hoenig]] (Summit 2013).\n\nIn The Asian Banker Summit 2008 in Hanoi and The Asian Banker Summit 2009 in Beijing, The Asian Banker collaborated with [[The Bankers' Association for Finance and Trade]] (BAFT) on a conference, held in conjunction with The Asian Banker Summit, called The BAFT Asia Conference on Cash, Treasury and Trade.<ref>[http://www.asianbankerforums.com/summit2008/conference_04.php The Asian Banker Summit 2008, BAFT Asia Conference on Cash, Treasury and Trade]. Asianbankerforums.com.</ref> On 27 October 2008, BAFT announced that it had renewed the agreement for the 2009 conference in Beijing.<ref>[http://www.aba.com/Press+Room/102708BAFTAsianBanker.htm American Bankers Association, 27 October 2008, \"BAFT and The Asian Banker Renew Agreement to Collaborate on Annual Asian Summit\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081203151844/https://www.aba.com/Press+Room/102708BAFTAsianBanker.htm |date=3 December 2008 }}. Aba.com.</ref>\n\nBesides the Summit, the company holds events in other cities around Asia.<ref>[http://www.asianbankerforums.com Asian Banker Forums]. Asian Banker Forums.</ref>\n\n==Research==\nThe Asian Banker launched a research division in 2003.<ref>[https://www.theasianbanker.com/A556C5/Research.nsf/frmResDtCtr?OpenForm Asian Banker Research] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070630004025/https://www.theasianbanker.com/A556C5/Research.nsf/frmResDtCtr?OpenForm |date=30 June 2007 }}</ref> [[Asian Banker Research]] business compiles rankings, such as Asia Pacific banks by asset size and financial strength, CEO compensation, dividend payouts, the top 40 Islamic banking institutions in Asia, a databook of macro indicators of banking, payments and distribution, and industry performance. The division also writes management reports, research notes, country reports, and proprietary benchmarking on consumer banking technology and operations, and other topics.\n\n===The Asian Banker 300===\nWhile The Asian Banker's research business covers a variety of research projects, its most visible product is [[The Asian Banker 300]], a reference guide to the 300 largest banks in Asia Pacific by assets. The company expands the list to over 500 banks in its online version. The research comes out in September or October and is launched every year at [[Sibos (conference)|Sibos]], the large annual financial services convention organised by [[SWIFT]]. In the 2008 financial year, the 10 largest banks in the Asia Pacific region by assets were [[Mitsubishi UFJ Financial Group]], [[Mizuho Financial Group]], [[Industrial and Commercial Bank of China]], [[Sumitomo Mitsui Financial Group]], [[China Construction Bank]], [[Agricultural Bank of China]], [[Bank of China]], [[Norinchukin Bank]], [[Hongkong and Shanghai Banking Corporation]] and [[National Australia Bank]]. This has been unchanged since the previous years.<ref name=\"The Asian Banker 300\">[http://www.asianbankerpublication.com/A556C5/Journals.nsf/frmJournal?OpenForm&Issue=92 The Asian Banker 300]</ref>\n\nSince 2003, the guide has added a strength ranking, which measures each of the 300 banks according to a strength formula.  The formula weights assets, year-on-year growth in loans, year-on-year growth in deposits, and eight other criteria to arrive at a total strength score.<ref name=\"The Asian Banker 300\"/> Invariably, the largest banks are not necessarily the strongest banks, and in the 2009 financial year, the 10 strongest banks in the Asia Pacific region were [[HDFC Bank]], [[Punjab National Bank]], [[Public Bank]], [[Bank of Nanjing]], [[Bank Central Asia]], [[China CITIC Bank]], [[ANZ Bank New Zealand|ANZ National Bank]], [[Union Bank of India]], [[Westpac Banking Corporation]] and [[China Construction Bank]].<ref>[http://www.asianbankerpublication.com/A556C5/Journals.nsf/frmJournal?OpenForm&Issue=92 The Asian Banker list of the 300 largest banks by assets in the Asia Pacific region]</ref> The ranking is a recognised benchmark among financial institutions in Asia, and banks that have mentioned the ranking in their investor relations materials and financial reports include [[Siam Commercial Bank]],<ref>[http://www.scb.co.th/en/abt/abt_awb_50.shtml About Siam Commercial Bank, Awards and Rankings, 2007]. Scb.co.th.</ref> [[Maybank]],<ref>[http://www.maybankcms.com.ph/recent_events.html Maybank, January 2008, Maybank Ranked Among Asia Pacific\u2019s Largest and Strongest Banks] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20080627010813/http://www.maybankcms.com.ph/recent_events.html |date=27 June 2008 }}. Maybankcms.com.ph.</ref> [[Shanghai Pudong Development Bank]],<ref>[http://www.spdb.com.cn/docpage/c522/200709/0930_522_15166.aspx Shanghai Pudong Development Bank, About Us, News, SPDB Ranked Top 3 Chinese Banks] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120122024227/http://www.spdb.com.cn/docpage/c522/200709/0930_522_15166.aspx |date=22 January 2012 }}. Spdb.com.cn.</ref> [[DBS Bank|DBS]],<ref>[http://www.dbs.com.sg/dbsgroup/annual2006/Pages/awards_and_accolades.htm DBS, Awards and Accolades, Hearing it from the Marketplace]. Dbs.com.sg.</ref> [[Bumiputra-Commerce Holdings]]<ref>[http://www.cimb.com/annual_reports/BCHB/2007/pdf/exec.pdf Bumiputra-Commerce Holdings Berhad, Annual Report, 2007] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091229115910/http://www.cimb.com/annual_reports/BCHB/2007/pdf/exec.pdf |date=29 December 2009 }}</ref> and [[Hang Seng Bank]].<ref>[http://www.hangseng.com/hsb/eng/abo/cc/csr/our_bus/main_ourbus.html Hang Seng Bank, Our Business] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081204135706/http://www.hangseng.com/hsb/eng/abo/cc/csr/our_bus/main_ourbus.html |date=4 December 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.theasianbanker.com/ Official Web Site]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100316215024/http://www.asianbankerpublication.com/ The Asian Banker Editorial]\n*[http://www.asianbankerforums.com/ The Asian Banker Forums]\n*[https://www.theasianbanker.com/A556C5/Journals.nsf/frmJournal?openform&Issue=84/ The Asian Banker Journal]{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n*[https://www.theasianbanker.com/A556C5/Research.nsf/frmResDtCtr?OpenForm/ The Asian Banker Research]{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Asian Banker}}\n[[Category:Financial services companies established in 1996]]\n[[Category:Financial services companies of Singapore]]\n[[Category:Banking industry]]\n", "name_user": "Toweli", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Asian_Banker"}
{"title_page": "Alif Bank", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=October 2019}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2015}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name                = Alif Bank\n| logo                = Official_logo_of_Alif_Bank_in_Tajikistan.png\n| type                = [[Open joint-stock company]]\n| industry            = [[Financial Services]]\n| founded             = {{Start date and age|df=yes|2014}}\n| hq_location_city    = [[Dushanbe]]\n| hq_location_country = [[Tajikistan]]\n| key_people          = Khofiz Shakhidi - Chairman of the board <br> Abdullo Kurbanov - CEO & co-founder <br> Zuhursho Rahmatulloev - co-founder <br> Firdavs Mirzoev - co-founder <ref name=\"chairman\">[https://www.thebanker.com/World/Alif-Bank-looks-to-further-international-expansion Alif Bank looks to further international expansion], Source [https://www.thebanker.com The Banker/Financial Times].</ref>\n| products            = [[Microfinance]] using [[Islamic banking]]\n| num_employees       = 300 (2020)\n| num_employees_year  = <!-- Year of num_employees data (if known) -->\n| website             = {{URL|https://www.alif.tj}}\n}}\n\n\nAlif Bank ([[Tajik language|Tajik]]: \u0410\u043b\u0438\u0444 \u0411\u043e\u043d\u043a, [[Russian language|Russian]]: \u0410\u043b\u0438\u0444 \u0411\u0430\u043d\u043a) or Alif Capital, Alif Sarmoya is a [[financial technology]] company, built on values and technologies. Alif uses the principles of [[Islamic banking|Islamic Finance]]. It is located in Dushanbe, Khujand, has a subsidiary in Tashkent and is currently expanding to other geographies. \n\n= History =\nAlif was founded in 2014. At that time the [[National Bank of Tajikistan]] (NBT) was working on instructions for financial institutions that wished to work under the principles of [[Islamic banking|Islamic Finance]]. Alif Capital had already used the principles of Islamic finance that did not conflict with the existing banking law and was therefore considered the first micro-financing organization that worked based on principles of Islamic banking.\n\nOver the following several years, the company has transformed into an ecosystem of technological and financial solutions for its clients. Alif is a market leader in POS financing through installment-based club-card, commission-free overdrafts, the largest online B2C platform (alif.shop), the most widely used mobile wallet (alif.mobi) in the country, and exclusive integration with the largest classifieds website. These services are facilitated by a number of internally developed complex software: Core Banking System, CRM, mobile wallet, card processing, HR & recruiting systems, built by Alif\u2019s team of 50+ software engineers. Having built these core strengths, Alif started expanding internationally, with its first office in Uzbekistan. \n\nAnother major milestone was achieved, when, in November 2019, Alif raised equity funding from Khofiz Shakhidi, a Tajik businessman in Monaco, helping Alif to convert into a full-fledged bank in Tajikistan in January 2020. \n\n= Timeline =\n\n* 2014 Alif Capital LLC was established and received a license from the [[National Bank of Tajikistan|NBT]] to operate as [[Microfinance|micro-credit]] organization on 29th April.\n* 2014 Alif Capital launched consumer credit which was dubbed as \u00ab\u0411\u0435\u0444\u043e\u0438\u0437\u00bb ([[Russian language|\u0440\u0443\u0441.]] \u0411\u0435\u0441\u043f\u0440\u043e\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u043d\u044b\u0439 [[English language|eng.]] Interest-free) by offering short-term consumer credits (4\u20136 months) to its clients. The main trading partners of this project are the major consumer brands in the country akin to Huyndai, VOLNA, Samsung, Technosila, Sinon, Kilim, Kamolot and others.\n* April 29, 2014 \u2014 First SME loan was financed.\n* June 10, 2014 \u2014 Opened investment account.\n* October 7, 2015 \u2014 CRM: Alif\u2019s first in-house Customer relationship management software was launched.\n* 2015 Over 9 months, Alif Capital increased its financing portfolio by over three times and, as a result, it became the 5th largest micro-credit organization among the members of AMFOT in Tajikistan. Alif Capital joined AMFOT (Association of Micro-credit Organizations of Tajikistan), the role of which is to unify and harmonize the interests of industry players by developing their capabilities to serve the general public more effectively.\n* March 18, 2016 \u2014 Received licence to operate as MDO - a microcredit and deposit organization. Now Alif could take deposits, make foreign exchange transactions, current account operations, and a much wider set of financial products could be introduced.\n* April 1, 2016 \u2014 Opened first deposit account.\n* January 1, 2017 \u2014 CBS: Alif\u2019s own in-house Core Banking System software was launched. Core Banking Systems are highly complex banking software that banks usually purchase from major international vendors. Alif took a significant step towards becoming a fintech company by writing and launching its own Core Banking System, which allows Alif to be self-sufficient, fast and flexible.\n* March 17, 2017 \u2014 Alif joined the national card processing center and started issuing Korti Milli cards (Korti Milli cards constitute the majority of cards in Tajikistan).\n* June 3, 2017 \u2014 alif shop: launched first online store with an option to purchase consumer goods on deferred payment service. Alif.shop later grew to become the largest online B2C marketplace in Tajikistan.\n* August 1, 2017 \u2014 Alif Academy: launched free programming courses.\n* October 16, 2017 \u2014 Began operating in Khujand.\n* November 4, 2017 \u2014 alif pay: launched the first online acquiring platform for Korti Milli in the country. Prior to Alif\u2019s online acquiring platforms, Korti Milli cards could not be used for online transactions, card to card transfers, etc. The system used by Alif was later widely adopted by other banks, ushering a period of fast fintech growth in the country. \n* January 6, 2018\u00a0 \u2014 alif mobi: introduced our online mobile wallet. Alif mobi today is the largest, most widely used and most highly rated mobile wallet in the country.\n* January 29, 2018 \u2014 Launched international remittances services.\n* March 15, 2018 \u2014 Nasia Card: launched an overdraft card with installments up to 10 days.\n* August 20, 2018 \u2014 Salom: launched Salom club card, which helps Alif\u2019s customers buy retail goods online and offline on installment basis with minimum effort. To support Salom cards Alif also developed a special software that turns regular smartphones into POS terminals, that are in turn used by merchants to process Salom transactions. Alif today is the market leader in Tajikistan on point-of-sale financing. \n* October 26, 2018 \u2014 alif online: created a site for monitoring operations and services used by clients.\n* March 12, 2019 \u2014 Alif Tech opened in Uzbekistan, Alif\u2019s first major step towards international expansion. Alif Tech, a subsidiary of Alif Capital, was granted IT Park resident status in the Republic of Uzbekistan. This residence provides tax incentives and conditions for IT development in the country.\n* September 13, 2019 \u2014 Alif Moliya opened in Uzbekistan, to provide retail financing to clients by means of alifshop.uz\n* October 2, 2019 \u2014 Alif Capital was granted certificate of excellence by the Tax Committee of the Republic of Tajikistan for fair implementation of tax legislation and significant contribution to the revenue part of the state budget.\n* In November 2019, Alif Capital raised additional capital from a successful Tajik businessman from Monaco [[Khofiz Shakhidi]], who in turn became a 25% shareholder in Alif and the Chairman of the Board . The funds attracted allowed Alif Capital to apply for a full bank license.\n* December 18, 2019 \u2014 Alif won the gold award \u00abBrand of the Year \u2014 2019. Peak of glory\u00bb. \n* In January 2020, Alif Capital has become a fully licensed bank  and officially renamed itself to Alif Bank.\n* In February 2020, CBH Bank (Compagnie Bancaire Helv\u00e9tique SA) - a private Swiss Bank bought a stake in Alif and became a shareholder.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Banks of Tajikistan]]\n[[Category:Islamic economic jurisprudence]]\n[[Category:Companies of Tajikistan]]\n[[Category:Microfinance companies of Asia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=October 2019}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2015}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Alif Bank\n| logo = Official_logo_of_Alif_Bank_in_Tajikistan.png\n| type = [[Open joint-stock company]]\n| industry = [[Financial Services]]\n| founded = {{Start date and age|df=yes|2014}}\n| hq_location_city = [[Dushanbe]]\n| hq_location_country = [[Tajikistan]]\n| key_people = Khofiz Shakhidi - Chairman of the board <br> Abdullo Kurbanov - CEO & co-founder <br> Zuhursho Rahmatulloev - co-founder <br> Firdavs Mirzoev - co-founder <ref name=\"chairman\">[https://www.thebanker.com/World/Alif-Bank-looks-to-further-international-expansion Alif Bank looks to further international expansion], Source [https://www.thebanker.com The Banker/Financial Times].</ref> \n| products = [[Microfinance]] using [[Islamic banking]]\n| num_employees = 290 (2019)\n| num_employees_year = <!-- Year of num_employees data (if known) -->\n| website = {{URL|https://www.alif.tj}}\n}}\n\n\nAlif Bank ([[Tajik language|Tajik]]: \u0410\u043b\u0438\u0444 \u0411\u043e\u043d\u043a, [[Russian language|Russian]]: \u0410\u043b\u0438\u0444 \u0411\u0430\u043d\u043a) or Alif Capital, Alif Sarmoya is a [[financial technology]] company, built on values and technologies. Alif uses the principles of [[Islamic banking|Islamic Finance]]. It is located in Dushanbe, Khujand, has a subsidiary in Tashkent and is currently expanding to other geographies. \n\n= History =\nAlif was founded in 2014. At that time the [[National Bank of Tajikistan]] (NBT) was working on instructions for financial institutions that wished to work under the principles of [[Islamic banking|Islamic Finance]]. Alif Capital had already used the principles of Islamic finance that did not conflict with the existing banking law and was therefore considered the first micro-financing organization that worked based on principles of Islamic banking.\n\nOver the following several years, the company has transformed into an ecosystem of technological and financial solutions for its clients. Alif is a market leader in POS financing through installment-based club-card, commission-free overdrafts, the largest online B2C platform (alif.shop), the most widely used mobile wallet (alif.mobi) in the country, and exclusive integration with the largest classifieds website. These services are facilitated by a number of internally developed complex software: Core Banking System, CRM, mobile wallet, card processing, HR & recruiting systems, built by Alif\u2019s team of 50+ software engineers. Having built these core strengths, Alif started expanding internationally, with its first office in Uzbekistan. \n\nAnother major milestone was achieved, when, in November 2019, Alif raised equity funding from Khofiz Shakhidi, a Tajik businessman in Monaco, helping Alif to convert into a full-fledged bank in Tajikistan in January 2020. \n\n= Timeline =\n\n* 2014 Alif Capital LLC was established and received a license from the [[National Bank of Tajikistan|NBT]] to operate as [[Microfinance|micro-credit]] organization on 29th April.\n* 2014 Alif Capital launched consumer credit which was dubbed as \u00ab\u0411\u0435\u0444\u043e\u0438\u0437\u00bb ([[Russian language|\u0440\u0443\u0441.]] \u0411\u0435\u0441\u043f\u0440\u043e\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u043d\u044b\u0439 [[English language|eng.]] Interest-free) by offering short-term consumer credits (4\u20136 months) to its clients. The main trading partners of this project are the major consumer brands in the country akin to Huyndai, VOLNA, Samsung, Technosila, Sinon, Kilim, Kamolot and others.\n* April 29, 2014 \u2014 First SME loan was financed.\n* June 10, 2014 \u2014 Opened investment account.\n* October 7, 2015 \u2014 CRM: Alif\u2019s first in-house Customer relationship management software was launched.\n* 2015 Over 9 months, Alif Capital increased its financing portfolio by over three times and, as a result, it became the 5th largest micro-credit organization among the members of AMFOT in Tajikistan. Alif Capital joined AMFOT (Association of Micro-credit Organizations of Tajikistan), the role of which is to unify and harmonize the interests of industry players by developing their capabilities to serve the general public more effectively.\n* March 18, 2016 \u2014 Received licence to operate as MDO - a microcredit and deposit organization. Now Alif could take deposits, make foreign exchange transactions, current account operations, and a much wider set of financial products could be introduced.\n* April 1, 2016 \u2014 Opened first deposit account.\n* January 1, 2017 \u2014 CBS: Alif\u2019s own in-house Core Banking System software was launched. Core Banking Systems are highly complex banking software that banks usually purchase from major international vendors. Alif took a significant step towards becoming a fintech company by writing and launching its own Core Banking System, which allows Alif to be self-sufficient, fast and flexible.\n* March 17, 2017 \u2014 Alif joined the national card processing center and started issuing Korti Milli cards (Korti Milli cards constitute the majority of cards in Tajikistan).\n* June 3, 2017 \u2014 alif shop: launched first online store with an option to purchase consumer goods on deferred payment service. Alif.shop later grew to become the largest online B2C marketplace in Tajikistan.\n* August 1, 2017 \u2014 Alif Academy: launched free programming courses.\n* October 16, 2017 \u2014 Began operating in Khujand.\n* November 4, 2017 \u2014 alif pay: launched the first online acquiring platform for Korti Milli in the country. Prior to Alif\u2019s online acquiring platforms, Korti Milli cards could not be used for online transactions, card to card transfers, etc. The system used by Alif was later widely adopted by other banks, ushering a period of fast fintech growth in the country. \n* January 6, 2018\u00a0 \u2014 alif mobi: introduced our online mobile wallet. Alif mobi today is the largest, most widely used and most highly rated mobile wallet in the country.\n* January 29, 2018 \u2014 Launched international remittances services.\n* March 15, 2018 \u2014 Nasia Card: launched an overdraft card with installments up to 10 days.\n* August 20, 2018 \u2014 Salom: launched Salom club card, which helps Alif\u2019s customers buy retail goods online and offline on installment basis with minimum effort. To support Salom cards Alif also developed a special software that turns regular smartphones into POS terminals, that are in turn used by merchants to process Salom transactions. Alif today is the market leader in Tajikistan on point-of-sale financing. \n* October 26, 2018 \u2014 alif online: created a site for monitoring operations and services used by clients.\n* March 12, 2019 \u2014 Alif Tech opened in Uzbekistan, Alif\u2019s first major step towards international expansion. Alif Tech, a subsidiary of Alif Capital, was granted IT Park resident status in the Republic of Uzbekistan. This residence provides tax incentives and conditions for IT development in the country.\n* September 13, 2019 \u2014 Alif Moliya opened in Uzbekistan, to provide retail financing to clients by means of alifshop.uz\n* October 2, 2019 \u2014 Alif Capital was granted certificate of excellence by the Tax Committee of the Republic of Tajikistan for fair implementation of tax legislation and significant contribution to the revenue part of the state budget.\n* In November 2019, Alif Capital raised additional capital from a successful Tajik businessman from Monaco [[Khofiz Shakhidi]], who in turn became a 25% shareholder in Alif and the Chairman of the Board . The funds attracted allowed Alif Capital to apply for a full bank license.\n* December 18, 2019 \u2014 Alif won the gold award \u00abBrand of the Year \u2014 2019. Peak of glory\u00bb. \n* In January 2020, Alif Capital has become a fully licensed bank  and officially renamed itself to Alif Bank.\n* In February 2020, CBH Bank (Compagnie Bancaire Helv\u00e9tique SA) - a private Swiss Bank bought a stake in Alif and became a shareholder.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Banks of Tajikistan]]\n[[Category:Islamic economic jurisprudence]]\n[[Category:Companies of Tajikistan]]\n[[Category:Microfinance companies of Asia]]\n", "name_user": "Ganjinas", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alif_Bank"}
